'''Derrick JaVaughn Byars''' (born April 25, 1984 in [[Memphis, Tennessee]]) is an American professional basketball player. Collegiality, he played for [[Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball|Virginia]], and later for [[Vanderbilt Commodores men's basketball|Vanderbilt]]. He was drafted 42nd overall in the [[2007 NBA Draft]].

==High school career==
Byars attended [[Ridgeway High School (Memphis, Tennessee)|Ridgeway High School]] in Memphis, where he played for head coach [[Wesley Henning]] and won two [[Tennessee Secondary School Athletic Association]] ([[TSSAA]]) Class AA State Championships.

As a [[wiktionary:sophomore|sophomore]] (1999<U+2013>2000), Byars was an honorable-mention All-State selection and led the Roadrunners to the Class AA State Championship. He averaged 16.4 [[Point (basketball)|points]], 6.5 [[Rebound (basketball)|rebounds]] and 5.4 [[Assist (basketball)|assists]] per game.

As a [[Eleventh grade|junior]], he again earned honorable mention All-State honors and was named Ridgeway's Most Valuable Player. He averaged 20.5 points, 7.2 rebounds and 5 assists.

As a [[Twelfth grade|senior]] (2001<U+2013>02), he averaged 23.2 points, 10 rebounds and 4.5 assists and led Ridgeway to its second TSSAA Class AA State Championship in three years. He was a fourth-team [[All-America#High school sports|Parade All-America]] selection, the Gatorade Player of the Year in Tennessee, the TSSAA Class AA Tournament Most Valuable Player and first-team All-State.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://virginiasports.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/byars_derrick00.html|title=Derrick Byars Profile (Virginia)|publisher=CSTV.com|accessdate = 2007-03-08}}</ref>

As impressive as he was on the court, Byars also excelled in the classroom, finishing [[high school]] with a 3.9 [[Grade (education)|GPA]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cavalierdaily.com/news/2002/nov/12/derrick-byars/ |title=Derrick Byars Inside Out |work=[[Cavalier Daily]] |date=2002-11-12 |last=Moss |first=J.D. |accessdate = 2007-03-08}}</ref>

==Collegiate career==
===Virginia===
Byars played for two seasons under then-Head Coach [[Pete Gillen]] at [[Virginia Cavaliers men's basketball|Virginia]]. He started 16 of Virginia's 31 games his freshman season (2002<U+2013>03) and averaged 6.5 points per game. In his sophomore season (2003<U+2013>04), he started 18 of Virginia's 31 games and averaged 7.5 points per game.<ref name=cstv.com>{{cite web |url=http://vucommodores.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/byars_derrick00.html|title=Derrick Byars Profile (Vanderbilt)|publisher=CSTV.com|accessdate = 2007-03-08}}</ref>

After falling out with Gillen, Byars decided to transfer from Virginia. Vanderbilt, fresh off a run to the Sweet 16 of the [[2004 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]], was his first choice, but the Commodores had no scholarship positions available. Days before Byars was due to announce his transfer to [[University of Mississippi|Mississippi]], Vanderbilt reserve guard Adam Payton decided to [[transfer]] to [[College of William & Mary|William & Mary]], freeing up a scholarship for Byars.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/19/sports/ncaabasketball/19vandy.html|title=Commodores' Success Is Built on Two Players Who Never Met|publisher=NYTimes.com|accessdate = 2007-03-19 | first=Lee | last=Jenkins | date=2007-03-19}}</ref>

He sat out the 2004<U+2013>05 season as mandated by NCAA rules.

===Vanderbilt===
In his junior season (2005<U+2013>06), Byars started all 30 games and finished second on the team in scoring at 12.4 points per game. He led the team with 3.2 assists per game. He was named SEC Player of the Week (28 November-4 December) after scoring 20 points on 7-of-8 shooting against [[Oregon Ducks|Oregon]] on November 30, 2005. A week later, he scored a season-high 25 points (including five 3-pointers) against [[Cincinnati Bearcats|Cincinnati]] on December 10, 2005.<ref name=cstv.com>{{cite web |url=http://vucommodores.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/byars_derrick00.html|title=Derrick Byars Profile 2006<U+2013>07|publisher=CSTV.com|accessdate = 2007-03-08}}</ref>

In his senior season (2006<U+2013>07), Byars was named [[Southeastern Conference]] Player of the Year by the league's coaches, who also unanimously selected him to their All-SEC first team. He led Vanderbilt to a 22<U+2013>12 record ([[Southeastern Conference|SEC East]]: 10<U+2013>6, 2nd) and the Sweet 16 of the [[2007 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]]. He led the Commodores in scoring with 17.0 points per game and was ranked among the SEC's top 10 in four other statistical categories. During SEC play, Byars averaged 19.1 points per game, second-best in the SEC. He scored 20 points or more eight different times, including a career-high 32 points against [[South Carolina Gamecocks|South Carolina]] on February 14, 2007. He followed that performance with 24 points in Vanderbilt's 83<U+2013>70 victory over then-No. 1 [[Florida Gators|Florida]], which earned him SEC player of the week honors for the second time that season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tennessean.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070308/SPORTS0602/703080416/1002|title=Coaches say Byars SEC's best|publisher=Tennessean.com |accessdate = 2007-03-08}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

Byars graduated from Vanderbilt on May 11, 2007 with a degree in sociology.

==Professional career==
===NBA===
Byars was chosen 42nd overall in the [[2007 NBA Draft]] in the second round by the [[Portland Trail Blazers]]. His rights were then traded to the [[Philadelphia 76ers]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tennessean.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=2007705090445|title=Byars may go late in first round|publisher=Tennessean.com|accessdate = 2007-05-14}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> He was waived by the 76ers on October 22, 2007. He was on the [[New Orleans Hornets]] and [[Orlando Magic]] rosters for the 2008 Summer League.  Byars return to the NBA Summer League was successful, as he led the Magic in scoring in their first game against the New Jersey Nets with 15 points on 6 of 13 shooting [http://www.nba.com/media/magic/Game_3_Box_Score.pdf]. 

In late September, Byars was signed by the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]] where he averaged 4.1 points and 14.8 minutes per game in the preseason.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/sports/article.aspx?articleID=20080930_226_B5_OKLAHO809612|title= Thunder Notebook|accessdate=2008-09-30|publisher= Tulsa World |date=2008-09-30}}</ref>

Byars was invited to the [[Chicago Bulls]] training camp in 2009 but was waived on the opening day of the season, October 28, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagobreakingsports.com/2009/10/bulls-starting-5.html |title=Bulls' starting 5?  |accessdate=2008-10-28 |publisher= Chicago Breaking Sports News |date=2008-10-28 }}</ref>

He played for the [[Chicago Bulls]] in the [[NBA Summer League]] in [[2010 in basketball|2010]].<ref>http://www.ridiculousupside.com/2010/6/28/1540775/nba-summer-league-rosters-vegas NBA Summer League Rosters - Vegas</ref>

===Germany===
In December 2007, Byars played in eight games for the [[K<U+00F6>ln 99ers]], a [[Basketball Bundesliga]] team based in [[Cologne]], [[Germany]], having arrived at the end of October with a foot injury that had to be cured first. He averaged 6.3 points and 18 minutes per game in four games in the [[ULEB Cup]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euroleague.net/competition/players/showplayer?clubcode=col&pcode=000685&seasoncode=u2007|title=Derrick Byars <U+2013> K<U+00F6>ln 99ers Game Log|publisher=Euroleague.net|accessdate = 2008-01-22}}</ref> and 3.5 points in another 4 games in the Bundesliga. He was cut from the team again on December 21, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koeln99ers.de/99ers/index3.php?cat=news&storyID=466|title=K<U+00F6>ln 99ers trennen sich von Derrick Byars (K<U+00F6>ln 99ers are separating from Derrick Byars)|language=German|publisher=K<U+00F6>ln 99ers Official Homepage|accessdate = 2008-03-06 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071231125543/http://www.koeln99ers.de/99ers/index3.php?cat=news&storyID=466 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-12-31}}</ref>

On November 2, 2009, Byars was introduced as the new small forward for [[ALBA Berlin]].

===France===
On January 24, 2008, he was subsequently signed by [[Chorale Roanne Basket]], a team that plays in the [[Ligue Nationale de Basketball]] (LNB) in [[France]] and is the defending 2007 national champion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurobasket.com/team.asp?Cntry=FRA&Team=417|title=Chorale Roanne Basket Current Roster|publisher=Eurobasket.com|accessdate = 2008-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chorale-roanne.com/?id=1&num=1475|title=Derrick Byars est choralien (Derrick Byars is a Choralien)|language=French|publisher=Chorale Roanne Official Homepage|accessdate = 2008-03-06}}</ref>

His club finished fourth in the 2007/08 regular season, and lost in the 2008 LNB final against [[SLUC Nancy|Nancy]] after beating regular season winner Le Mans in the semi-final. 
Byars averaged 8 points and 3 rebounds in 24 minutes of playing time.<ref>[http://www.lnb.fr/index.php?pid=9&id=A41010&from=2007&type=1 Ligue Nationale de Basket<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

===NBDL===
Derrick Byars later played in the NBA Developmental League for the Bakersfield Jam. He was named to the 2009 NBDL All-Star Game. He returned to the team briefly in 2011.

===Greece===
In September 2010, he signed a one-year deal with the [[HEBA A1 Ethniki|Greek]] club [[Panellinios Basket]].<ref>[http://www.eurocupbasketball.com/ulebcup/home/on-court/transactions/eurocup-2010-11/i/75588/4674/panellinios-signs-derrick-byars PANELLINIOS signs Derrick Byars.]</ref>

===Return to France===
In August 2011 he signed a one-year contract with [[Cholet Basket]] in [[France]].<ref>[http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/86995/180/cholet-basket-signs-byars Cholet Basket signs Byars]</ref>. However, he leaves the club in November, having played only two games, one in [[2011-12 LNB season|Pro A]] and one in [[Euroleague 2011<U+2013>12 qualifying rounds|Euroleague qualifying round]]<ref>{{fr}}{{Citeweb |url=http://www.cholet-basket.com/news/actualites/derrick-byars-quitte-cholet-basket-n5104.htm |title= Derrick Byars quitte Cholet |publisher=cholet-basket.com |date=November 12, 2011}}</ref>.

===Return to the NBA===
On December 10, 2011, the [[Miami Heat]] announced that they had signed Byars to a NBA Contract.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/heat/news/heat_signs_derrick_byars_111210.html]</ref>

==Awards and accomplishments==
*All-[[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] First Team: (2007)
